V{{About|the Harvard political philosopher, Norman Daniels}}\u000a\u000a{{Infobox scientist\u000a| name = Norman Daniels\u000a|image = \u000a| image_size =\u000a| caption =\u000a| residence = [[Massachusetts]], USA\u000a| citizenship = USA\u000a| ethnicity = Jewish American\u000a| field = [[global health]], [[population health]], health ethics, philosophy, ethics\u000a| work_institutions = [[Tufts University]], [[Tufts University School of Medicine]], [[Harvard School of Public Health]], [[Harvard University]]\u000a| birth_date = 1942\u000a| birth_place = New York\u000a| nationality = American (USA)\u000a| known_for = political philosophy; a theory of justice which includes health possibilities and healthcare ethics; moral epistemology; allocation of resources; public goods\u000a| awards = Investigator Award in Health Policy Research, Robert Wood Johnson Foundation<ref>[http://www.investigatorawards.org/investigators/norman-daniels Award page for RWJF Investigator Award in Health Policy Research]</ref>\u000a| death_date =\u000a| death_place =\u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Norman Daniels''', born in 1942, is an [[American philosopher|American political philosopher]] and [[philosopher of science]], [[political theorist]], [[ethicist]], and [[bioethics|bioethicist]] at [[Harvard University]].<ref>[http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/faculty/norman-daniels/ HSPH faculty profile]</ref>  Before his career at Harvard, Daniels had built his career as a [[medical ethics|medical ethicist]] at [[Tufts University School of Medicine]], also in [[Boston]].\u000a\u000a==Teaching positions==\u000aDaniels is [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/faculty/norman-daniels/ Mary B. Saltonstall Professor of Population Ethics and Professor of Ethics and Population Health] in the [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/departments/population-and-international-health/ Department of Global Health and Population] at the [[Harvard School of Public Health]] in Boston.\u000a\u000aPreviously, and for 33 years, he had taught political philosophy at [[Tufts University]] in [[Medford, Massachusetts]].<ref>[http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/benchmark/ndaniels/pdf/justice_health.pdf Justice, Health, and Healthcare, an article on political and social justice vis a vis access to healthcare, while Norman Daniels taught at Tufts]</ref><ref>http://www.eqv.name/biographies/Bios_63-64.htm#_Toc128730656</ref>  At [[Tufts University]], he was Goldthwaite Professor and Chair of the Philosophy Department, and at [[Tufts University School of Medicine]], he was Professor of [[Medical Ethics]] (1969\u20132002).<ref>[http://ethics.harvard.edu/people/current-role/faculty-associates Faculty Associates of the Edward J. Safra Center for Ethics at Harvard, noting some of the topical areas which Dr. Daniels researches]</ref>\u000a\u000a==Education==\u000a* 1970 - [[Harvard University]], Ph.D. (Philosophy), awarded the Plympton Dissertation Prize, 1971<ref>[http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/benchmark/ndaniels/bio_7_2008.html Biosketch: Norman Daniels, personal homepage]</ref>\u000a* 1966 - [[Balliol College]], [[Oxford]], B.A. (equivalent to M.A. in USA) (Philosophy and Psychology, First Honors)\u000a* 1964 - [[Wesleyan University]], B.A. (English, Summa cum Laude)\u000a\u000a==Personal==\u000aDaniels is married to neuro-psychologist Anne Lacy Daniels (Ed.D.).<ref>[http://healthprovidersdata.com/hipaa/codes/NPI-1104030949-dr-anne-lacy-daniels-anne-daniels-edd Health Providers Data for Anne Lacy Daniels, EdD]</ref>  They have one son, Noah M. Daniels, a postdoctoral research associate at MIT.<ref>[http://people.csail.mit.edu/ndaniels/ MIT CSAIL profile for Noah M. Daniels, PhD]</ref>\u000a\u000aWith [[Jared Israel]], Daniels co-chaired the Harvard chapter of the [[Students for a Democratic Society]] in 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F50F14FA395E1B7493C0A9178ED85F4D8685F9|title=169 Fined in Harvard Sit-In; 2 Cleared at Cambridge|accessdate=February 9, 2009|author=Robert M. Smith|date=May 2, 1969|publisher=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10D14FD3B5B1A7B93CBA9178ED85F438685F9|title=70 Youths Ejected In Protest on Draft At House Building|accessdate=February 9, 2009|date=May 9, 1967|publisher=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8115756.html|title=Harvard, Ex-Radicals Remember Many Talk of Feelings 20 Years After Protest|accessdate=February 9, 2009|author=Alexander Reid|date=April 9, 1989|publisher=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>\u000a\u000aIn a public letter to his fraternity brothers at Wesleyan, Daniels wrote: "At Harvard, I ended up co-chair of SDS and gave the speech on the steps of University Hall April 9, 1969, that began the take-over of that administration building and thus led to the Harvard Strike. I would have been fired as a teaching fellow, so I followed my advisors advice and quit that position to take a part-time job at Tufts, teaching philosophy of science and political philosophy. I stayed 33 years."<ref>http://www.eqv.name/biographies/Bios_63-64.htm#_Toc128730656</ref>\u000a\u000a==Professional affiliations==\u000a* Formerly Goldthwaite Professor and Chair of the Philosophy Department at [[Tufts University]] and Professor of [[Medical Ethics]] at [[Tufts University School of Medicine|Tufts Medical School]], 1969\u20132002\u000a* Fellow, [[Hastings Center]]\u000a* Member, [[Institute of Medicine]]\u000a* Founding Member of the [http://www.nasi.org National Academy of Social Insurance]\u000a* Member, [http://www.iseqh.org International Society for Equity in Health]\u000a* Member, Medicare Coverage Advisory Commission (Bill Clinton administration)\u000a* Member, Ethics Working Group of the Clinton White House Health Care Task Force (Spring 1993)\u000a* Member, Advisory Board of the CIHR-Institute of Population and Public Health (Fall 2009)\u000a* Member, Ethics Advisory Board of the [[Centers for Disease Control]] (Fall 2009 - Fall 2012)\u000a* Member, Public Health Service Expert Panel on Cost Effectiveness and Clinical Preventive Medicine\u000a* Member, National Academy of Social Insurance study panel on the social role of [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]]\u000a* Member, [http://www.tcf.org/ Century Fund] task force on [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] reform\u000a\u000a'''Consulting'''\u000a* He has consulted with organizations, commissions, and governments in the U.S. and abroad on issues of justice and health policy\u000a* Consultant, [[United Nations]]\u000a* Consultant, [[World Health Organization]]\u000a* President's Commission for the Study of Ethical Problems in Medicine\u000a\u000a==Books==\u000a* [https://books.google.com/books?id=YCRg-y6ujEUC&dq=Norman+Daniels&printsec=frontcover&source=an&hl=en&ei=39jQSvTVIdHelAeSgp2pCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=11&ved=0CDAQ6AEwCg#v=onepage&q=&f=false Thomas Reid's`Inquiry': the Geometry of Visibles and the Case for Realism] (1974; Stanford, 1989)\u000a* Reading Rawls (1975; Stanford, 1989)\u000a* [https://books.google.com/books?id=0875k5cZjWcC&dq=Norman+Daniels&printsec=frontcover&source=an&hl=en&ei=39jQSvTVIdHelAeSgp2pCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CCgQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=&f=false Just Health Care] (Cambridge, 1985)\u000a* Am I My Parents' Keeper? An Essay on Justice Between the Young and the Old (Oxford, 1988)\u000a* Seeking Fair Treatment: From the AIDS Epidemic to National Health Care Reform Oxford, 1995)\u000a* Justice and Justification: Reflective Equilibrium in Theory and Practice (Cambridge University Press, 1996)\u000a* (with Donald Light and Ronald Caplan) Benchmarks of Fairness for Health Care Reform (Oxford, 1996)\u000a* (with [[Allen Buchanan]], [[Daniel Brock|Dan Brock]], and [[Dan Wikler]]) [https://books.google.com/books?id=mj0JsDKE1poC&dq=%22from+chance+to+choice+genetics+and+justice%22&pg=PP1&ots=l75YcmD3RL&sig=s3-v0rJzczdfACBjwNKPg2cL4L4&hl=en&prev=http://www.google.com/search?q=%22From+Chance+to+Choice:+Genetics+and+Justice%22&ie=utf-8&oe=utf-8&rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&client=firefox-a&sa=X&oi=print&ct=title&cad=one-book-with-thumbnail  From Chance to Choice: Genetics and Justice]. [http://www.cambridge.org/ Cambridge University Press]. ISBN 0-521-66977-4. (Cambridge, 2000)\u000a* (with Bruce Kennedy and [[Unnatural Causes: Is Inequality Making Us Sick?|Ichiro Kawachi]]) Is Inequality Bad for Our Health? (Beacon Press, 2000)\u000a* (with James Sabin) Setting Limits Fairly: Can We Learn to Share Medical Resources? (Oxford, 2002;2nd ed., 2008)\u000a* [https://books.google.com/books?id=DrVLvi0r6JIC&dq=Norman+Daniels&printsec=frontcover&source=an&hl=en&ei=39jQSvTVIdHelAeSgp2pCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CCwQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=&f=false Just Health: Meeting Health Needs Fairly] (Cambridge, 2008).\u000a\u000a[Source: [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/benchmark/ndaniels/publications.html Bibliography of books, from personal webpage, which also includes peer-reviewed journal articles and book chapters published since 1965]]\u000a\u000a==Awards==\u000a\u000a* Member, [[Institute of Medicine]]\u000a* Fellow, [[The Hastings Center]]\u000a* Founding Member, National Academy of Social Insurance\u000a* Founding Member, International Society for Equity in Health\u000a* Founding Member, National Cancer Policy Board, established by the [[Institute of Medicine]] and the Commission on the Life Sciences (served He served four years)\u000a* Founding Member, Advisory Board of the Open Society Foundation project on Medicine as a Profession, and on the International Bioethics Advisory Board of PAHO. He served recently on an IOM Committee on the use of Cost Effectiveness Analysis in regulatory contexts.\u000a\u000a==Fellowships and grants==\u000a* Greenwall Foundation\u000a* [[National Endowment for the Humanities]]\u000a* [[National Institutes of Health]]\u000a* [[National Library of Medicine]]\u000a* [[National Science Foundation]]\u000a* Retirement Research Foundation\u000a* [[Robert Wood Johnson Foundation]]\u000a: Investigator Award in Health Policy Research, Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, 1997 (for the period 1998-2001)\u000a: "Limit-Setting in Managed Care and Other Health Delivery Systems: Legitimacy, Fair Process, and the Goals of Health Care Reform"<ref>[http://www.investigatorawards.org/investigators/norman-daniels Award page for RWJF Investigator Award in Health Policy Research]</ref>\u000a* [[Rockefeller Foundation]] grant, international adaptation of the benchmarks\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[American philosophy]]\u000a* [[List of American philosophers]]\u000a* [[List of Jewish American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a<references/>\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/faculty/norman-daniels/ HSPH Faculty Site for Prof. Norm Daniels]\u000a* [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/faculty/norman-daniels/publications/ Publications of Prof. Norm Daniels]\u000a* [http://jme.bmj.com/content/vol35/issue1/ 'Norman Daniels Symposium' lectures/papers presented published in the Journal of Medical Ethics (January 2009, Volume 35, Number 1), published by British Medical Journal and the Institute of Medical Ethics]\u000a* [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/benchmark/ndaniels/ HSPH-sponsored personal Faculty website for Prof. Norman O. Daniels, PhD]\u000a\u000a{{Subject bar\u000a| portal1=Philosophy\u000a| portal2=Medicine\u000a| portal3=United States\u000a| portal4=Biography\u000a}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Daniels, Norman}}\u000a[[Category:1942 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:American academics]]\u000a[[Category:American ethicists]]\u000a[[Category:American Jews]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Jewish philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\u000a[[Ca